    title: 'Vital Signs Monitoring',
    category: 'industry',
    description: 'Vital signs monitoring is the systematic measurement and interpretation of core physiological parameters including blood pressure, heart rate, respiratory rate, temperature, and oxygen saturation (SpO2). These five measurements serve as the primary indicators of a patient\'s hemodynamic stability and overall clinical status. Many facilities now include pain assessment as a sixth vital sign.\n\nModern vital signs monitoring relies on both manual techniques (auscultation, palpation) and automated technologies such as continuous pulse oximetry, cardiac telemetry, capnography, and non-invasive blood pressure monitors. Early warning scoring systems like NEWS2 (National Early Warning Score) and MEWS (Modified Early Warning Score) use vital sign trends to detect clinical deterioration before it becomes critical.\n\nProficiency in vital signs monitoring includes the ability to obtain accurate readings, recognize abnormal values and trends, and escalate findings appropriately. Healthcare professionals must understand the clinical significance of findings such as tachycardia, hypotension, tachypnea, and desaturation in the context of the patient\'s underlying condition.',
